**Description of the problem including expected versus actual behavior**:
In order to avoid indexing request being rejected, Elasticsearch validates that no index template defines the alias used when rolling over an index. This validation is in place in order to avoid the case where newly created indices will match an index template whose alias contains the rollover alias, in which case the rollover alias would point to multiple indices.

However, if we have a legacy template that defines the rollover alias and a composable template that "overrides" the legacy template and doesn't define the rollover alias, this validation should not be triggered (because the composable template takes precedence over the legacy template and it is valid) 


**Steps to reproduce**:
```
--
PUT _template/legacy
{
  "index_patterns": ["te*", "bar*"],
  "settings": {
    "number_of_shards": 1
  },
  "aliases" : {
    "alias1" : {}
  }
}

--
PUT _index_template/newtemplate
{
  "index_patterns": ["te*", "bar*"],
  "template": {
    "settings": {
      "number_of_shards": 2
    }
  }
}

--
PUT testindex
{
  "aliases": {
    "alias1": {}
  }
}

--
POST alias1/_rollover/testindex-000002
```

Rolling over in this case would yield:
```
{
  "error": {
    "root_cause": [
      {
        "type": "illegal_argument_exception",
        "reason": "Rollover alias [alias1] can point to multiple indices, found duplicated alias [[alias1]] in index template [legacy]"
      }
    ],
    "type": "illegal_argument_exception",
    "reason": "Rollover alias [alias1] can point to multiple indices, found duplicated alias [[alias1]] in index template [legacy]"
  },
  "status": 400
}
```

